# Supabase Patterns

## Client Setup
- Server components: use `createServerClient` from `@supabase/ssr`
- Client components: use `createBrowserClient` (rare — avoid when possible)
- API routes: use `createRouteHandlerClient`
- Never import `supabase` directly — always use factory functions from `lib/supabase/`

## Query Patterns
```typescript
// lib/supabase/queries.ts — centralized queries
export async function getSuburbBySlug(slug: string) {
  const supabase = createServerClient();
  const { data, error } = await supabase
    .from('suburbs')
    .select('*')
    .eq('slug', slug)
    .eq('is_published', true)
    .single();
  if (error) throw new Error(`Suburb not found: ${slug}`);
  return data;
}
```

## Tables
- `suburbs`: slug, name, region, meta_title, meta_description, h1, content, faq_json, schema_json
- `services`: slug, name, type, parent_slug, meta_title, meta_description, content, faq_json, pricing_json
- `blog_posts`: slug, title, meta_title, meta_description, content, excerpt, featured_image, published_at
- `pages`: slug, title, template, meta_title, meta_description, content, schema_json
- `images`: url, alt_text, original_filename, size_kb, page_type
- `regions`: slug, name, meta_title, content, suburbs (TEXT[])

## Row Level Security
- Enable RLS on ALL tables
- Public read policy: `USING (is_published = true)` for all content tables
- No public write access — writes only via service key in server functions
